00:16:05.892 --> 00:16:09.872
patients without alteration compared to 55%

265
00:16:09.932 --> 00:16:12.592
in patient with genomic alteration.

266
00:16:13.772 --> 00:16:17.532
Now here we summarize the baseline gene

267
00:16:17.632 --> 00:16:21.372
alteration profile in G12C inhibitor-refractory cohort by

268
00:16:21.432 --> 00:16:25.352
ctDNA analysis. Amongst 31 analyzed

269
00:16:25.392 --> 00:16:28.592
patients, about 70% of patients had a

270
00:16:28.652 --> 00:16:31.592
detectable KRAS G12C at baseline,

271
00:16:31.972 --> 00:16:35.272
confirming ongoing KRAS dependency even

272
00:16:35.372 --> 00:16:38.272
after a prior G12C inhibitor treatment.

273
00:16:38.932 --> 00:16:42.352
Notably, 16% of patients had KRAS

274
00:16:42.452 --> 00:16:45.512
amplification, a well-known resistant mechanism to

275
00:16:45.552 --> 00:16:49.432
G12C inhibitor. In addition, a broad range

276
00:16:49.612 --> 00:16:53.292
of alterations such as RTK, PI3K, MAP

277
00:16:53.312 --> 00:16:57.172
kinase, and other pathway alterations were observed, highlighting the

278
00:16:57.232 --> 00:17:00.512
molecular heterogeneity and complexity of this

279
00:17:00.552 --> 00:17:01.252
population.

280
00:17:02.572 --> 00:17:02.792
Here

281
00:17:03.972 --> 00:17:07.613
we show the efficacy of elacestrant in G12C

282
00:17:07.652 --> 00:17:11.341
inhibitor-refractory patient with KRAS amplification.

283
00:17:11.792 --> 00:17:15.512
As you can see here, 60% of patients achieved confirmed partial

284
00:17:15.532 --> 00:17:19.052
response with 100% disease control rate and

285
00:17:19.232 --> 00:17:22.692
40% continued study treatment, and

286
00:17:23.532 --> 00:17:27.152
67% of patients achieved partial response

287
00:17:27.613 --> 00:17:29.592
six weeks after treatment.

288
00:17:31.172 --> 00:17:34.932
Regarding molecular response, 60% of

289
00:17:34.992 --> 00:17:38.932
patients achieved molecular response as early as cycle one, day

290
00:17:39.112 --> 00:17:42.932
eight, and then complete G12C clearance at

291
00:17:43.012 --> 00:17:46.292
cycle four, day one. And this indicates

292
00:17:46.732 --> 00:17:50.632
elacestrant's complete and fast target engagement may

293
00:17:50.672 --> 00:17:54.652
address resistance mediated by KRAS amplification.

294
00:17:55.512 --> 00:17:58.752
Now we show acquired genomic alteration

295
00:17:59.512 --> 00:18:02.632
in G12C inhibitor-naive patients.

296
00:18:03.252 --> 00:18:03.632
Paired

297
00:18:05.292 --> 00:18:09.032
baseline and EOT ctDNA analysis was performed in

298
00:18:09.212 --> 00:18:13.172
18 patients with PFS longer than three

299
00:18:13.252 --> 00:18:15.612
months. And at EOT,

300
00:18:16.632 --> 00:18:19.432
no KRAS amplification was detected in

301
00:18:19.712 --> 00:18:23.492
G12C inhibitor-naive cohort. This implies

302
00:18:23.552 --> 00:18:27.352
that elacestrant's complete and rapid target engagement

303
00:18:27.412 --> 00:18:28.662
may reduce the

304
00:18:29.752 --> 00:18:32.962
emergence of KRAS amplification as acquired resistance

305
00:18:32.972 --> 00:18:36.672
mechanism and correlate with its

306
00:18:36.712 --> 00:18:40.008
clinical efficacy in this patient population.So in

307
00:18:40.028 --> 00:18:43.428
conclusion, elacridar monotherapy demonstrated

308
00:18:43.588 --> 00:18:47.308
robust and durable efficacy in G12C naive

309
00:18:47.648 --> 00:18:51.328
and G12C inhibitor refractory population at RP2d.

310
00:18:51.728 --> 00:18:55.618
Objective response rate was 58.8%,

311
00:18:55.888 --> 00:18:59.688
and median PFS was 12.2 months. Amongst

312
00:18:59.748 --> 00:19:03.628
G12C inhibitor refractory population, objective response rate

313
00:19:03.688 --> 00:19:06.968
was 32% with a median PFS of

314
00:19:07.508 --> 00:19:11.228
8.1 months. Importantly, in five patients with

315
00:19:11.448 --> 00:19:15.068
KRAS amplification, ORR was 60%.

316
00:19:15.528 --> 00:19:19.508
The safety profile of elacridar remains favorable and

317
00:19:19.628 --> 00:19:22.328
consistent with phase one dose escalation.

318
00:19:22.868 --> 00:19:26.708
We observed this ctDNA of deep and

319
00:19:27.308 --> 00:19:31.258
rapid molecular response without the emergence of KRAS amplification,

320
00:19:31.528 --> 00:19:33.857
which correlate with the differentiated

321
00:19:34.768 --> 00:19:37.148
mechanism of action of elacridar.

322
00:19:37.748 --> 00:19:40.908
Based on this promising efficacy and safety data,

323
00:19:41.508 --> 00:19:45.248
elacridar monotherapy received BTD and fast track

324
00:19:45.328 --> 00:19:47.588
designation in NLCLC,

325
00:19:48.448 --> 00:19:51.948
which warrants pivotal trial of monotherapy in

326
00:19:52.068 --> 00:19:54.848
combination with checkpoint inhibitor in frontline setting.

327
00:19:55.768 --> 00:19:59.468
Lastly, we thank all patients and the family, clinical trial

328
00:19:59.588 --> 00:20:02.668
staff that participate in this trial. Thank you for your attention.

329
00:20:08.988 --> 00:20:12.408
Thank you very much, Dr Chou. And now to put the

330
00:20:12.468 --> 00:20:15.388
increasingly complex and differentiated field of

331
00:20:15.448 --> 00:20:18.748
G12C inhibitors in non-small cell lung cancer, it's

332
00:20:18.788 --> 00:20:22.568
an honor to invite Dr Sacher, who's going to speak to us on this

333
00:20:22.608 --> 00:20:23.008
topic.

334
00:20:24.228 --> 00:20:24.528
Thank you.

335
00:20:29.908 --> 00:20:32.898
Thank you for the kind introduction, and I would like to thank the organizing

336
00:20:32.988 --> 00:20:35.848
committee for the invitation to discuss this abstract.

337
00:20:37.128 --> 00:20:38.068
These are my disclosures.

338
00:20:39.828 --> 00:20:43.628
KRAS constitutes a challenging target requiring an entirely new

339
00:20:43.648 --> 00:20:46.908
therapeutic paradigm. We know that it is a difficult to target

340
00:20:46.948 --> 00:20:50.428
GTPase. It has a complex downstream signaling

341
00:20:50.508 --> 00:20:54.338
pathway with associated tendency towards compensatory feedback and is

342
00:20:54.388 --> 00:20:56.848
also associated with a unique immunobiology.

343
00:20:57.568 --> 00:21:01.068
Newly developed KRAS inhibitor classes each have complex and distinct

344
00:21:01.188 --> 00:21:05.128
mechanisms, including both the KRAS G12C off inhibitors, which we

345
00:21:05.148 --> 00:21:08.748
will focus on today, as well as the newer tricomplex and dual state

346
00:21:08.828 --> 00:21:10.648
KRAS G12C on inhibitors.

347
00:21:12.288 --> 00:21:15.948
KRAS G12C off inhibitors covalently bind the switch II binding

348
00:21:16.028 --> 00:21:19.788
pocket of GDP bound KRAS G12C, thus locking it

349
00:21:19.848 --> 00:21:23.458
into its inactive state. There are multiple agents in this drug

350
00:21:23.548 --> 00:21:27.068
class, each utilizing a similar mechanism but exhibiting variable

351
00:21:27.168 --> 00:21:31.048
potency, variable response rate, as well as variable toxicity.

352
00:21:33.168 --> 00:21:37.048
Indeed, there are a large number of such off inhibitors approved during

353
00:21:37.088 --> 00:21:40.408
development, including the original, arguably less potent

354
00:21:40.508 --> 00:21:43.928
sotorasib and adagrasib, as well as newer agents like

355
00:21:43.968 --> 00:21:47.788
divorasib, alomorasib, calderasib, elacridar, and

356
00:21:47.828 --> 00:21:48.438
many others.

357
00:21:50.528 --> 00:21:53.668
Sotorasib was the original KRAS G12C off inhibitor

358
00:21:54.568 --> 00:21:56.348
and in many ways set the tone for the field.

359
00:21:56.778 --> 00:22:00.468
The best data for sotorasib come from the CodeBreaK 200 randomized study of

360
00:22:00.528 --> 00:22:04.368
sotorasib versus docetaxel in the later line setting in non-small cell lung

361
00:22:04.408 --> 00:22:08.218
cancer. Here we saw a modest but real response rate with

362
00:22:08.268 --> 00:22:11.998
sotorasib of 28.1%. And although sotorasib

363
00:22:12.048 --> 00:22:15.988
improved progression-free survival in this later line population, it did

364
00:22:15.998 --> 00:22:18.648
not significantly change overall survival.

365
00:22:19.948 --> 00:22:23.928
In contrast, newer and more potent inhibitors like divorasib

366
00:22:23.968 --> 00:22:26.978
have exhibited still modest but improved response rates.

367
00:22:27.348 --> 00:22:31.278
Here you can see from an early phase study of divorasib a response rate of

368
00:22:31.488 --> 00:22:35.137
53.4% and a more durable PFS at

369
00:22:35.148 --> 00:22:36.528
13.1 months.

370
00:22:37.668 --> 00:22:41.588
And we are looking forward to ongoing studies comparing divorasib to sotorasib and

371
00:22:41.648 --> 00:22:43.488
adagrasib in the later line setting.

372
00:22:45.348 --> 00:22:49.268
As you probably gathered, primary and acquired resistance are the key challenges

373
00:22:49.288 --> 00:22:52.828
for KRAS G12C off inhibitors, where we see these modest response

374
00:22:52.888 --> 00:22:56.588
rates. We are still elucidating these mechanisms of resistance,

375
00:22:56.728 --> 00:23:00.368
but key mechanisms include compensatory pathway activation and

376
00:23:00.448 --> 00:23:04.028
overdrive. Essentially anything that keeps KRAS in its active

377
00:23:04.088 --> 00:23:07.888
GTP-bound state will resist binding to a GDP-based inhibitor.

378
00:23:08.568 --> 00:23:12.548
As well as other mechanisms like KRAS amplification, alternative KRAS

379
00:23:12.628 --> 00:23:16.348
variants, drug binding pocket alterations, bypass pathway

380
00:23:16.408 --> 00:23:19.148
alterations, and even histologic transformation.

381
00:23:20.848 --> 00:23:24.808
We've also come to note that KRAS G12C off inhibitors are associated

382
00:23:24.848 --> 00:23:28.668
with unique mechanisms of toxicity, notably immune-mediated

383
00:23:28.688 --> 00:23:32.278
hepatitis, which occurs oddly only in PD-1 experienced

384
00:23:32.388 --> 00:23:36.008
patients. We've encountered this with the original inhibitors like

385
00:23:36.068 --> 00:23:39.648
sotorasib, and indeed, in the case of sotorasib, the degree of

386
00:23:39.708 --> 00:23:43.068
autoimmune hepatitis experienced precluded combinations with

387
00:23:43.108 --> 00:23:47.048
immunotherapy. We've also seen it with newer inhibitors like divorasib

388
00:23:47.068 --> 00:23:47.628
and others.

389
00:23:49.668 --> 00:23:53.008
This brings me to the key question that I always ask myself whenever I see data on

390
00:23:53.068 --> 00:23:56.048
a new KRAS G12C inhibitor in this very crowded space.

391
00:23:56.158 --> 00:24:00.008
And that question really is: Does the world need another KRAS G12C

392
00:24:00.088 --> 00:24:01.128
off inhibitor?

393
00:24:02.068 --> 00:24:05.898
But I always approach this question fairly and logically, and I tend to apply the

394
00:24:06.048 --> 00:24:09.908
same rubric for evaluating novel inhibitors.

395
00:24:10.568 --> 00:24:14.168
Specifically, I like to think carefully about the frequency of primary resistance

396
00:24:14.208 --> 00:24:17.328
as well as the potency of the inhibitor, and this usually comes through in the

397
00:24:17.368 --> 00:24:21.028
response rate. I like to think carefully about the mechanism as well as the

398
00:24:21.108 --> 00:24:24.388
speed of acquired resistance that we see in these patients, which you can usually

399
00:24:24.398 --> 00:24:27.788
divine from the PFS. And then I look closely at

400
00:24:27.828 --> 00:24:31.668
toxicity barriers, especially autoimmune hepatitis, as well as the

401
00:24:31.708 --> 00:24:35.348
ability of a new agent to overcome acquired resistance to other agents

402
00:24:35.888 --> 00:24:39.288
and its activity in difficult to treat subsets, namely STK11,

403
00:24:39.408 --> 00:24:41.668
KEAP1, and PDL1 negative patients.

404
00:24:42.288 --> 00:24:45.718
Truly, the utility of a new KRAS G12C inhibitor hinges on these

405
00:24:45.748 --> 00:24:49.678
parameters, both when we think about it as a more optimal monotherapy as

406
00:24:49.708 --> 00:24:53.508
well as a foundation for future combination therapy.We

407
00:24:53.548 --> 00:24:57.388
saw data today on elacrasib from an early phase study looking at both

408
00:24:57.428 --> 00:25:01.268
KRAS G12C inhibitor naive and refractory non-small cell lung

409
00:25:01.348 --> 00:25:02.208
cancer patients.

410
00:25:03.868 --> 00:25:07.708
And looking first at the toxicity of this drug, we did see that treatment

411
00:25:07.728 --> 00:25:11.028
discontinuation due to toxicity was rare in this study.

412
00:25:11.088 --> 00:25:14.728
However, dose interruption and dose reduction were more common.

413
00:25:15.708 --> 00:25:19.688
The primary toxicity that we saw from elacrasib was GI in

414
00:25:19.728 --> 00:25:23.648
nature, and the majority of these cases were Grade 1 or

415
00:25:23.728 --> 00:25:27.688
Grade 2. There was a signal of autoimmune hepatitis consistent with

416
00:25:27.708 --> 00:25:30.648
this class of drugs. The frequency

417
00:25:31.468 --> 00:25:34.318
was relatively low, and most of these cases were low grade.

418
00:25:34.908 --> 00:25:38.668
However, it is important to note in this study that 10% of patients had

419
00:25:38.728 --> 00:25:42.368
not had a previous checkpoint inhibitor, and the

420
00:25:42.408 --> 00:25:46.068
majority of patients were more than 60 days out from their previous checkpoint

421
00:25:46.088 --> 00:25:50.068
inhibitor, which means that the study may underestimate the actual risk

422
00:25:50.128 --> 00:25:54.068
of autoimmune hepatitis, given that both of these would reduce the frequency

423
00:25:54.168 --> 00:25:56.258
of this event in this population.

424
00:25:57.688 --> 00:26:01.408
Turning now to efficacy in the G12C naive population, we

425
00:26:01.468 --> 00:26:05.348
saw a favorable response rate compared to other potent inhibitors in this field

426
00:26:05.358 --> 00:26:09.028
with a response rate of 53.6% across dose levels

427
00:26:09.448 --> 00:26:12.768
and 52.9% at the Phase 2 dose.

428
00:26:14.488 --> 00:26:17.948
Progression-free survival was 9.4 months across dose levels and

429
00:26:17.968 --> 00:26:20.528
12.2 at the Phase 2 dose.

430
00:26:22.048 --> 00:26:25.668
Looking at the G12C refractory cohort, before we look at the data, it's

431
00:26:25.708 --> 00:26:29.358
important to note that the majority of these patients received previous,

432
00:26:29.428 --> 00:26:33.288
older, less potent inhibitors, and most patients, or at least half of

433
00:26:33.308 --> 00:26:35.948
patients, were more than 60 days out from their previous inhibitor.

434
00:26:36.428 --> 00:26:39.888
This raises the question of how many of these responses are true

435
00:26:39.988 --> 00:26:43.028
circumvention of an acquired resistance mechanism versus just

436
00:26:43.208 --> 00:26:47.088
reresponse in a patient where sensitive clones have grown out again

437
00:26:47.188 --> 00:26:49.388
after holding a previous G12C inhibitor.

438
00:26:50.988 --> 00:26:54.048
Nonetheless, with those caveats, we did see a response rate of

439
00:26:54.188 --> 00:26:57.068
25.8% in this difficult-to-treat population

440
00:26:58.248 --> 00:27:00.188
and a median PFS of 8.1 months.

441
00:27:01.947 --> 00:27:05.428
Last but not least, we also saw a signal of potential activity amongst more

442
00:27:05.528 --> 00:27:09.468
difficult to treat subsets like STK11 and KEAP1 co-mutated patients.

443
00:27:10.608 --> 00:27:14.398
And thus to return to our key performance measures, I think it's clear that

444
00:27:14.428 --> 00:27:18.128
elacrasib demonstrates a favorable response rate relative to other highly potent

445
00:27:18.148 --> 00:27:21.708
inhibitors in this setting. We also saw

446
00:27:21.888 --> 00:27:23.508
evidence of durable PFS.

447
00:27:24.448 --> 00:27:27.928
There is still a signal of autoimmune hepatitis consistent with the field, and this

448
00:27:27.948 --> 00:27:31.708
will need to be watched carefully as we should watch with all KRAS G12C off

449
00:27:31.748 --> 00:27:32.248
inhibitors.

450
00:27:33.088 --> 00:27:36.768
And we did see the ability, potentially with the caveats that I mentioned, of

451
00:27:36.808 --> 00:27:40.748
elacrasib to overcome acquired resistance to other agents, as well as

452
00:27:40.808 --> 00:27:43.668
activity in difficult-to-treat subsets.

453
00:27:43.728 --> 00:27:47.568
Thus, the early-phase data here do support elacrasib as a promising KRAS

454
00:27:47.628 --> 00:27:51.388
G12C off inhibitor as monotherapy with potential for combination

455
00:27:51.468 --> 00:27:54.808
therapy in the future. That being said, elacrasib is not

456
00:27:54.868 --> 00:27:58.048
emerging into the field in a vacuum.

457
00:27:58.058 --> 00:28:00.737
It is emerging late into an extremely crowded field.

458
00:28:01.188 --> 00:28:04.888
The reality is that the modest clinical activity of existing KRAS G12C off

459
00:28:04.988 --> 00:28:08.498
inhibitor monotherapy has led to a rapid push to develop combination

460
00:28:08.608 --> 00:28:12.308
strategies. Indeed, KRAS G12C and immunotherapy

461
00:28:12.368 --> 00:28:16.017
strategies are already well along in development, particularly in the

462
00:28:16.048 --> 00:28:18.538
frontline setting in metastatic non-small cell lung cancer.

463
00:28:19.188 --> 00:28:22.888
We've also seen EGFR antibody-based combinations, which were pioneered in

464
00:28:22.928 --> 00:28:26.568
colorectal cancer, now begin to transit into the frontline setting in

465
00:28:26.628 --> 00:28:30.548
non-small cell lung cancer, as well as many other novel combination strategies

466
00:28:30.568 --> 00:28:31.248
in development.

467
00:28:32.108 --> 00:28:35.888
There are also newer efforts to develop KRAS on, pan-KRAS, and RAS

468
00:28:35.948 --> 00:28:39.768
inhibitors that are extremely promising in terms of mechanism and property

469
00:28:39.848 --> 00:28:41.668
relative to the older off inhibitors.

470
00:28:42.768 --> 00:28:46.428
To quickly touch on some recent data, we've seen data presented on

471
00:28:46.448 --> 00:28:50.318
calderacib plus pembrolizumab in PD-L1 positive KRAS G12C mutant

472
00:28:50.368 --> 00:28:52.468
metastatic non-small cell lung cancer recently.

473
00:28:53.308 --> 00:28:57.028
Important highlights include that the response rate amongst PD-L1 high patients

474
00:28:57.068 --> 00:29:01.048
with this combination was 87%, and the PFS in this

475
00:29:01.268 --> 00:29:04.128
subset of PD-L1 high patients has not yet been reached.

476
00:29:05.808 --> 00:29:09.428
In tandem, we've seen the rise of KRAS G12C on tri-complex

477
00:29:09.448 --> 00:29:13.168
inhibitors, including eloronrasib, which work on the on state

478
00:29:13.288 --> 00:29:15.548
via formation of an inhibitory tri-complex.

479
00:29:16.408 --> 00:29:20.388
And indeed, we've seen interesting early data on eloronrasib in

480
00:29:20.408 --> 00:29:23.948
KRAS G12C off acquired resistance, where a response rate of

481
00:29:24.108 --> 00:29:26.988
42% has been observed in a small cohort of patients.

482
00:29:28.068 --> 00:29:31.888
And interestingly, we have not seen the same signal of autoimmune

483
00:29:31.908 --> 00:29:34.008
hepatitis with this newer class of drugs.

484
00:29:34.948 --> 00:29:38.868
We've also seen the rise and proliferation of

485
00:29:38.908 --> 00:29:42.848
direct KRAS G12C on and pan-KRAS inhibitors utilizing a

486
00:29:42.888 --> 00:29:46.618
newer dual state targeting mechanism, which allows for simultaneous

487
00:29:46.728 --> 00:29:49.308
binding to both the inactive and active state of KRAS.

488
00:29:49.908 --> 00:29:53.338
This approach allows for rapid blockade of KRAS signaling in both states

489
00:29:53.868 --> 00:29:57.688
and offers the potential to overcome pathway overdrive, as well as many of the

490
00:29:57.748 --> 00:30:01.678
common mechanisms of primary resistance that we postulate have

491
00:30:01.708 --> 00:30:04.278
occurred in KRAS G12C off inhibitors.

492
00:30:04.688 --> 00:30:08.428
And again, there are many agents rapidly in development utilizing this

493
00:30:08.528 --> 00:30:09.168
mechanism.

494
00:30:10.728 --> 00:30:14.648
So to close, I would like to envision the future of KRAS G12C in non-small cell

495
00:30:14.688 --> 00:30:18.088
lung cancer. It's clear the KRAS G12C off inhibitors have

496
00:30:18.148 --> 00:30:21.768
revolutionized the field. Monotherapy has entered standard of care, and it

497
00:30:21.808 --> 00:30:25.348
continues to be optimized. Combinations are under intense

498
00:30:25.448 --> 00:30:28.968
investigation and have significant lead time over newer

499
00:30:29.048 --> 00:30:32.618
agents. All that being said, we really do need greater

500
00:30:32.628 --> 00:30:36.208
understanding of the mechanisms of primary and acquired resistance, as well as

501
00:30:36.217 --> 00:30:39.888
approaches to circumvent them, and greater understanding of the peculiar

502
00:30:39.928 --> 00:30:43.467
autoimmune toxicity associated with these drugs to guide

503
00:30:43.528 --> 00:30:46.840
rational development.Novel KRAS G12C on

504
00:30:46.880 --> 00:30:50.660
tri-complex and dual state inhibitors may overcome the fundamental limits of

505
00:30:50.740 --> 00:30:54.420
off inhibitors. We've seen evidence of activity in primary and acquired

506
00:30:54.460 --> 00:30:57.180
