Delati and colleagues. Yesterday and today, we heard about the

1736
01:45:23.124 --> 01:45:25.804
incredible chemistry and the development of

1737
01:45:25.844 --> 01:45:29.654
CID078. So today, I'll be taking a bit more of a

1738
01:45:29.664 --> 01:45:33.584
background approach. My talk is titled "Cyclin AB Inhibition: The

1739
01:45:33.664 --> 01:45:34.644
Next Mile in Cell

1740
01:45:35.504 --> 01:45:37.744
Cycle Therapy." These are my disclosures.

1741
01:45:41.204 --> 01:45:44.884
So cells enter G1 when activated for cell division by

1742
01:45:45.024 --> 01:45:48.784
stimuli, growth factors, hormones, and environmental changes.

1743
01:45:49.584 --> 01:45:53.564
Cyclin D rises, binds to and activates CDK4 and

1744
01:45:53.604 --> 01:45:56.664
CDK6. Cyclin E binds CDK2.

1745
01:45:57.764 --> 01:46:01.004
These complexes phosphorylate Rb, releasing it from

1746
01:46:01.044 --> 01:46:04.484
E2F and allowing E2F to transcribe genes needed for

1747
01:46:04.644 --> 01:46:05.104
S-phase.

1748
01:46:07.764 --> 01:46:11.544
The Cyclin A CDK2 complex initiates and regulates DNA

1749
01:46:11.564 --> 01:46:13.204
replication during S-phase.

1750
01:46:14.144 --> 01:46:18.024
This complex directly binds to E2F, phosphorylating it to

1751
01:46:18.064 --> 01:46:20.164
inhibit its DNA-binding activity.

1752
01:46:21.224 --> 01:46:25.084
This mechanism acts as a feedback loop that terminates the E2F-driven

1753
01:46:25.244 --> 01:46:28.824
S-phase transcriptional program and limits DNA replication to once per

1754
01:46:28.904 --> 01:46:29.244
cycle.

1755
01:46:31.604 --> 01:46:35.404
At the G2M checkpoint, the CDK Cyclin B complex

1756
01:46:35.464 --> 01:46:39.164
exists in an inactivated state due to phosphorylation by

1757
01:46:39.184 --> 01:46:40.564
PKMIT1 and WEE1.

1758
01:46:41.584 --> 01:46:45.504
CDC25B and 25C activate

1759
01:46:45.524 --> 01:46:49.164
the CDK1 Cyclin B complex through dephosphorylation, leading to

1760
01:46:49.184 --> 01:46:49.924
mitosis.

1761
01:46:53.004 --> 01:46:56.664
In normal cells, there's a coordinated and effective DNA

1762
01:46:56.744 --> 01:47:00.664
damage response. DNA damage causes DNA breaks, which

1763
01:47:00.704 --> 01:47:04.384
are sensed by ATM and ATR, which activate CHK1,

1764
01:47:04.604 --> 01:47:06.034
CHK2, and p53.

1765
01:47:07.524 --> 01:47:11.304
p53 transcribes p21, which inhibits the formation of the

1766
01:47:11.324 --> 01:47:13.183
Cyclin E CDK2 complex.

1767
01:47:14.264 --> 01:47:17.964
Rb is therefore not phosphorylated, preventing E2F-mediated

1768
01:47:18.004 --> 01:47:18.734
transcription.

1769
01:47:19.864 --> 01:47:23.544
Similarly, p21 inhibits the Cyclin B CDK1

1770
01:47:23.604 --> 01:47:24.164
complex,

1771
01:47:25.404 --> 01:47:29.044
and therefore, the cell cycle halts, allowing DNA repair or

1772
01:47:29.084 --> 01:47:29.964
apoptosis.

1773
01:47:32.624 --> 01:47:35.604
In cancer, the cell cycle is frequently dysregulated.

1774
01:47:36.694 --> 01:47:40.384
Mutations or altered expression of proteins that regulate the cell cycle are

1775
01:47:40.424 --> 01:47:44.334
common, and you can see these little red lightning bolts showing just some of

1776
01:47:44.384 --> 01:47:48.334
the more commonly mutated or altered cell cycle proteins in cancer.

1777
01:47:49.444 --> 01:47:53.104
These alterations allow for division of abnormal cells, promotes

1778
01:47:53.124 --> 01:47:56.924
genomic diversity among cancer cells, leading to the emergence of aggressive

1779
01:47:57.004 --> 01:48:00.444
and/or resistant clones, but can also provide a therapeutic

1780
01:48:00.524 --> 01:48:02.824
vulnerability as seen during today's sessions.

1781
01:48:05.224 --> 01:48:09.044
Replication stress and loss of coordinated checkpoints leads

1782
01:48:09.084 --> 01:48:12.084
to exaggerated dependencies on specific proteins.

1783
01:48:13.144 --> 01:48:17.053
There is increasing exploration of drugs targeting these proteins, working

1784
01:48:17.084 --> 01:48:20.444
by synthetic lethality. The molecular

1785
01:48:20.484 --> 01:48:24.324
alteration that creates the specific synthetic lethal relationship varies

1786
01:48:24.364 --> 01:48:27.523
based on the target. So for example, CCNE1

1787
01:48:27.624 --> 01:48:30.973
amplification is a common biomarker for PKMIT1,

1788
01:48:31.204 --> 01:48:34.724
WEE1, CHK1 and CHK2, and CDK2 inhibitors,

1789
01:48:34.984 --> 01:48:38.764
whereas ATM and BRCA mutations are common biomarkers for ATR

1790
01:48:38.804 --> 01:48:39.364
inhibitors.

